# Next.js App Router — Structure & Conventions

## Directory Layout

```
src/
  app/
    layout.tsx                         ← Root layout only (nav sidebar, header)
    page.tsx                           ← Redirect to /investments
    investments/
      page.tsx                         ← Server Component — fetches entity list
      InvestmentsListClient.tsx        ← "use client" list (filters + table)
      [id]/
        page.tsx                       ← Server Component shell (loads entity + resources)
        InvestmentDetailClient.tsx     ← "use client" detail view
    resources/page.tsx                 ← In progress
    api/
      [resource]/route.ts              ← Collection: GET, POST
      [resource]/[id]/route.ts         ← Instance: GET, PATCH, DELETE
  lib/                                 ← Pure business logic — no Next.js imports here
  generated/prisma/                    ← Auto-generated — NEVER edit manually
```

## Rules

- Keep route handlers **thin** — move all business logic to `src/lib/`.
- **Feature-based co-location:** keep related components, styles, and tests together.
- Avoid deeply nested directories; keep structure flat.
- Use **kebab-case** for directory names (e.g. `auth-form`).
- Use **PascalCase** for component filenames (e.g. `ResourceCard.tsx`).
- Use **absolute imports** via the `@/` alias from `tsconfig.json`.
  Never use relative paths like `../../components/...`.
- Use `loading.tsx` for route-level loading states.
- Use `error.tsx` for route-level error boundaries.
- **Canonical routes only.** No legacy paths (`/api/products`, `/api/test/*`, `/initiatives`)
  are active — do not create redirects or references to them.

## Naming Conventions

| Artefact         | Convention                            |
|------------------|---------------------------------------|
| Components       | `PascalCase.tsx`                      |
| Hooks            | `useHookName.ts`                      |
| API routes       | `route.ts` (one file per directory)   |
| Lib utilities    | `camelCase.ts`                        |
| Types/interfaces | `types.ts` or co-located in module    |
